// Negative fixture for nexus-x5ww — `let _ = e` must reject when `e`
// produces a structurally-linear (non-auto-droppable) value. Pre-fix the
// wildcard discard slipped through unchecked, silently leaking the
// linear resource. Post-fix `infer_let` rejects the binding directly,
// naming the offending source line and referencing the linearity rule.
//
// The x5ww fix is currently REVERTED on main (8b902d3 reverts cee07a5).
// Until it re-lands this fixture is the deferred / would-be-failing
// shape: against current main it compiles cleanly (the bug is live);
// against the re-landed fix it must fail typecheck. The companion
// `_test.nx` only exercises the auto-droppable %i64 path that remains
// valid in both states.
//
// Filename intentionally omits `_test` so `nexus test` does not pick it
// up — a fixture that intentionally fails compile would otherwise be
// reported as a runner failure.
import * as bb from "std:bytebuffer"

let main = fn () -> unit do
  // bb.empty() returns %ByteBuffer (linear, non-auto-droppable). The
  // `let _ = ...` wildcard discard must be rejected post-fix because the
  // structural pass cannot prove the inner type is auto-droppable —
  // accepting it would silently drop the buffer.
  let _ = bb.empty()
  return ()
end
